oyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, France","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Cecile, Lucien, Gilles, Normand, Marcel, Adelard, Jacques, Jean-Paul, Laurent, Alphonse.","French: habitational name from Soucy, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Soucie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Laurent, Ludger, Pierre.","Altered form of French   Soucy  ."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anna de Toucy was born about 1062, her father, Itier II de TOUCY, was 29 and her mother, Béatrix Béatrice de SENS, was 34. She married Milon de Noyers II in 1080, in Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1104, in Noyon, Oise, Picardie, France, at the age of 43."},"et":{"environ 1062–1104":"umbes 1062–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1056–1104":"1056–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1035–Male":"1035–Surnud","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","environ 1062":"umbes 1062","1120":"1120","ABT 1090":"umbes 1090","1030":"1030","1062":"1062","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1062–1104":"noin 1062–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1056–1104":"1056–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1035–Male":"1035–Kuollut","1030–Female":"1030–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","environ 1062":"noin 1062","1120":"1120","ABT 1090":"noin 1090","1030":"1030","1062":"1062","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Ranska","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Ranska","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, O